{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":9036,"record_hash":"sha256:b423557637de199d87f70d1a3347e62366c109316e9eedc4d20ddf29da66f1e9","timestamp":"2026-05-07T20:23:18.737Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 64b49e\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1634\nOutput:\n# GitMeta Data Model\n\n## Principles\n\n- Use GitMeta standard keys where they fit.\n- Use GitButler-specific keys only for capture bookkeeping.\n- Preserve transcript records as JSONL-compatible strings in local-only storage.\n- Use `git-meta-lib` as the storage abstraction; do not reimplement custom Git\n  metadata refs/branches in GitButler.\n- Avoid pretending a session belongs to a commit or branch when that is not\n  known.\n- Keep local capture cheap; serialize later at push/sync boundaries.\n- Prefer a conservative `project` target in the POC over misleading branch or\n  commit inference.\n\nGitMeta stores metadata as `(target, key, value)` tuples. Supported target types\ninclude `commit`, `change-id`, `branch`, `path`, and `project`. Keys are\nnamespace-like strings split on `:`, and list values are append-friendly logs.\n\n## Standard Agent Keys\n\nGitMeta recommends these agent keys:\n\n```text\nagent:provider\nagent:model\nagent:session-id\nagent:prompt\nagent:summary\nagent:transcript\n```\n\n`agent:transcript` is a list where each item is a JSONL record encoding a\nmessage, content, and tool calls. This is the likely future publishable/indexed\nformat, but it is not first-POC storage.\n\n## POC Storage Model\n\nFor the first implementation, write to `project` unless `--target` is explicit.\nDo not write publishable `agent:*` keys in the POC. Keep all captured state\nunder GitButler local-only keys until there is an explicit mapping and\npublication policy.\n\nMinimum useful writes:\n\n```text\nmeta:local:gitbutler:agent-session:<agent>:<session-key>:session-id = <raw-session-id>\nmeta:local:gitbutler:agent-session:<agent>:<session-key>:source-path = <path>\nmeta:local:gitbutler:agent-session:<agent>:<session-key>:source-size = <decimal-bytes>\nmeta:local:gitbutler:agent-session:<agent>:<session-key>:source-sha256 = <hash>\nmeta:local:gitbutler:agent-session:<agent>:<session-key>:last-record-index = <decimal-index>\nmeta:local:gitbutler:ag\n[TRUNCATED]\non that GitMeta keys reject. The raw\nsession id should still be stored as a value.\n\nRecommended keys:\n\n```text\nmeta:local:gitbutler:agent-session:<agent>:<session-key>:session-id\nmeta:local:gitbutler:agent-session:<agent>:<session-key>:source-path\nmeta:local:gitbutler:agent-session:<agent>:<session-key>:source-size        # decimal string\nmeta:local:gitbutler:agent-session:<agent>:<session-key>:source-sha256\nmeta:local:gitbutler:agent-session:<agent>:<session-key>:last-record-index  # decimal string\nmeta:local:gitbutler:agent-session:<agent>:<session-key>:captured-at\nmeta:local:gitbutler:agent-session:<agent>:<session-key>:cwd\nmeta:local:gitbutler:agent-session:<agent>:<session-key>:tool-version\nmeta:local:gitbutler:agent-session:<agent>:<session-key>:seen-record-hashes              # set<sha256>\nmeta:local:gitbutler:agent-session:<agent>:<session-key>:transcript-record-hashes        # set<sha256>\n```\n\nThese keys are implementation details. They help make capture idempotent and\nauditable, but other GitMeta clients do not need to understand them. Do not copy\nor mirror them into publishable namespaces until an explicit allowlist publication\npolicy exists.\n\n## Target Choices\n\n### Project Target\n\nUse `project` for the POC and whenever no branch, commit, or change id is\navailable. This is safer than inventing a relationship. Project-scoped records\ncan later link to branch or commit targets if better information becomes\navailable.\n\n### Branch Target\n\nUse `branch:<name>` when a hook explicitly provides a branch or when repository\nstate is unambiguous enough for a later milestone.\n\nBranch targets are useful for active coding work because sessions often precede\ncommits and may survive commit rewrites, but they can be misleading in stacked\nbranch, detached HEAD, or virtual/workspace situations.\n\n### Commit Target\n\nUse `commit:<sha>` only when a commit id is explicit. Good sources include:\n\n- a GitButler action that just created commits\n- a hook payload with exact commit ids\n- a user-provided `--target commit:<sha>`\n\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T20:23:18.737Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}